Iron Depletion effect on cell lines

0. Introduction

The purpose of this analysis is to examine gene expression data from a pure cell line that has undergone iron depletion, and see what’s happening in terms of IRE gene enrichment.

We will be using a dataset from GEO with accession number GSE32369. The title of this study is Effect of iron chelators on global gene expression pattern in SW480 cells, where the SW480 cell line is derived from colon cancer. Unfortunately I couldn’t find any RNA-seq datasets so this one is also a microarray dataset

The summary of the dataset is:

Gene expression analysis of SW480 cells treated with inhibitor compounds for 6 hours. Results provide insights into the role of iron in Wnt signalling and demonstrate that iron depletion is the primary mode of actions of these compounds on Wnt pathway.

SW480 cells were incubated with 10 mM of compounds (OICR623), control (DMSO) and two known iron chelators (DFO and Deferasirox) for 6 hours. RNA was extracted and cDNA samples isolated from 2-4 independent experiments were hybridized to the Affymetrix GeneChip® Human Gene 1.0 ST array.

The iron chelators DFO and Deferasirox are relevant to our work.

1. Data Import

The expression and sample data was imported from GEO as follows:

counts <- getGEO("GSE32369", GSEMatrix = TRUE)

samples <- counts$GSE32369_series_matrix.txt.gz %>% 
  phenoData() %>% 
  pData %>% 
  as_tibble

counts <- counts$GSE32369_series_matrix.txt.gz %>%
  exprs()

Preview the data:

counts %>% as.data.frame %>% rownames_to_column("gene_id") %>% as_tibble
samples

We will clean up the sample metadata and keep the relevant columns only.

samples %<>% dplyr::select(title, 
                          geo_accession,
                          characteristics_ch1.2) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(
    sample = title, 
    id = geo_accession, 
    treatment = characteristics_ch1.2
    ) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    treatment = gsub(x=treatment,
                     pattern = "^.* |\\(|\\)", 
                     replacement=""),
    treatment = as.factor(treatment)
  ) %>%
  arrange(treatment)

Check the “id” column in samples corresponds to the sampleNames.

sampleNames <- colnames(counts)
samples$id %in% sampleNames # Are all samples in sample table present in counts samples?
 [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
samples$id == sampleNames # Is the order the same?
 [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE

The ordering of samples isn’t the same across the sample table and the counts matrix, so we’ll reorder the counts.

counts[, samples$id] %>% dim

[1] 32321    13
sampleNames <- colnames(counts)
samples$id %in% sampleNames # Are all samples in sample table present in counts samples?
 [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
samples$id == sampleNames # Is the order the same?
 [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

2. Analysis

We are really only interested in whether IRE gene enrichment is present. However, to do this, we need to set up a voom obect ala limma.
